<div class="span12 widget-span widget-type-cell blog-content" style="padding-right: -200px" data-widget-type="cell" data-x="0" data-w="12">

<div class="row-fluid-wrapper row-depth-1 row-number-3 ">
<div class="row-fluid ">
<div class="span12 widget-span widget-type-custom_widget " style="" data-widget-type="custom_widget" data-x="0" data-w="12">
<div id="hs_cos_wrapper_module_1523032069834331" class="hs_cos_wrapper hs_cos_wrapper_widget hs_cos_wrapper_type_module widget-type-blog_content" style="" data-hs-cos-general-type="widget" data-hs-cos-type="module">
    <div class="blog-section">
<div class="blog-post-wrapper cell-wrapper">
<div class="section post-header">
<h1>Exploring the Clinical Applications of Virtual Reality in Healthcare</h1>
<ul class="post-page-meta">
<li>
<span>Posted on</span> August 21, 2023</li>
<li>
<span>By</span>
<a href="https://blog.victech.com/author/joshua-engle-md" rel="author">
Joshua Engle, MD
</a>
</li>
</ul>                  
</div>
<div class="section post-body">
<span id="hs_cos_wrapper_post_body" class="hs_cos_wrapper hs_cos_wrapper_meta_field hs_cos_wrapper_type_rich_text" style="" data-hs-cos-general-type="meta_field" data-hs-cos-type="rich_text"><p><img src="https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2258560561.jpg?width=2720&amp;height=1278&amp;name=shutterstock_2258560561.jpg" width="2720" height="1278" loading="lazy" alt="shutterstock_2258560561" style="height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 2720px;" srcset="https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2258560561.jpg?width=1360&amp;height=639&amp;name=shutterstock_2258560561.jpg 1360w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2258560561.jpg?width=2720&amp;height=1278&amp;name=shutterstock_2258560561.jpg 2720w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2258560561.jpg?width=4080&amp;height=1917&amp;name=shutterstock_2258560561.jpg 4080w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2258560561.jpg?width=5440&amp;height=2556&amp;name=shutterstock_2258560561.jpg 5440w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2258560561.jpg?width=6800&amp;height=3195&amp;name=shutterstock_2258560561.jpg 6800w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2258560561.jpg?width=8160&amp;height=3834&amp;name=shutterstock_2258560561.jpg 8160w" sizes="(max-width: 2720px) 100vw, 2720px"></p>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/joshua-engle-a8286a5/" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><img src="https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png?width=243&amp;height=355&amp;name=JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png" alt="JoshuaEngle_Headshot" width="243" height="355" loading="lazy" style="height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 243px; float: right; margin: 0px 0px 0px 10px;" srcset="https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png?width=122&amp;height=178&amp;name=JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png 122w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png?width=243&amp;height=355&amp;name=JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png 243w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png?width=365&amp;height=533&amp;name=JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png 365w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png?width=486&amp;height=710&amp;name=JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png 486w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png?width=608&amp;height=888&amp;name=JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png 608w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png?width=729&amp;height=1065&amp;name=JoshuaEngle_Headshot.png 729w" sizes="(max-width: 243px) 100vw, 243px"></a><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><span style="font-weight: bold; color: #073763;">Background: </span></span></p>
<p>While most people think of virtual reality as a source of entertainment, there are potential clinical applications of virtual reality. In this article, we will explore some of the most promising clinical applications of VR, the data from peer-reviewed studies with regards to the effectiveness of VR in these clinical settings, the FDA landscape in the clinical VR space, and payer reimbursement for VR clinical solutions. Finally, we will end with a prediction as to whether VR clinical solutions will get mainstream adoption in healthcare. Please note that in this article I focus on the patient facing applications of VR in healthcare. There are another group of applications on provider side, from provider training (most notably in surgery) to radiology applications, that are not discussed in this article. If there is sufficient interest, I can write a companion piece to this article exploring those healthcare applications of VR.</p>
<!--more-->
<p><span style="color: #073763;"><strong><u>Psychiatric Applications of Virtual Reality:</u></strong></span></p>
<p>The psychiatric applications of virtual reality revolve around virtual reality exposure therapy (VRET). VRET involves the use of VR to create realistic, immersive environments used for the purpose of providing therapeutic benefit to patients. The two principle psychiatric applications of VRET are below:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Phobia and Anxiety Disorders:</strong> Patients can face their fears in a controlled setting, gradually exposing them to their anxiety triggers. The hypothesis is VRET can help treat conditions like social anxiety disorder (SAD), agoraphobia, claustrophobia, acrophobia (fear of heights), arachnophobia (fear of spiders), and more.</li>
<li><strong>Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD):</strong> Patients are gradually exposed to trauma-related stimuli, allowing them to confront and process their trauma in a safe environment.</li>
</ol>
<p><img src="https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2149322047-1.png?width=445&amp;height=279&amp;name=shutterstock_2149322047-1.png" width="445" height="279" loading="lazy" alt="shutterstock_2149322047-1" style="height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 445px; float: right; margin: 0px 0px 0px 10px;" srcset="https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2149322047-1.png?width=223&amp;height=140&amp;name=shutterstock_2149322047-1.png 223w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2149322047-1.png?width=445&amp;height=279&amp;name=shutterstock_2149322047-1.png 445w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2149322047-1.png?width=668&amp;height=419&amp;name=shutterstock_2149322047-1.png 668w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2149322047-1.png?width=890&amp;height=558&amp;name=shutterstock_2149322047-1.png 890w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2149322047-1.png?width=1113&amp;height=698&amp;name=shutterstock_2149322047-1.png 1113w, https://blog.victech.com/hs-fs/hubfs/shutterstock_2149322047-1.png?width=1335&amp;height=837&amp;name=shutterstock_2149322047-1.png 1335w" sizes="(max-width: 445px) 100vw, 445px">When assessing the clinical validity of VRET, it is important to have a lay of the land for the gold standard treatment(s). This allows us to compare VRET against these interventions. Most therapies include both pharmaceutical and non-pharmaceutical interventions. For the sake of this article, we will focus on the non-pharmaceutical interventions as the gold-standards of comparison, as presumably that would be the piece of the treatment plan VRET would be augmenting/acting as an alternative to. Phobias/anxiety and PTSD mainstay treatment both involve use of cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT). Treatment of phobias also frequently involve the addition of in-vivo exposure therapy. This involves gradually exposing the patient in a controlled manner to whatever stressor is causing the patient anxiety. In-vivo means the exposure is real life exposure. For example, if a patient has a public speaking phobia, the in-vivo exposure therapy would mean exposing the patient gradually to public speaking. For PTSD, since there are usually specific extreme events leading to the patient having PTSD, and since these events are often hard to introduce in a controlled manner, imagination therapy in which the patient imagines the stimulus is often employed.</p>
<p>VRET has undergone clinical validation studies, and there have been systematic reviews with corresponding meta-analysis studies . A combined effort from Baylor University, UT Austin, and the San Francisco VA conducted a meta-analysis on 30 studies that investigated the effectiveness of VRET [1]. VRET versus both placebo and in-vivo therapy for specific phobias, SAD, panic disorder, and PTSD was studied. They reported their findings in terms of effect size. When compared to placebo, a small effect size means that VRET performed comparably to placebo. When compared to in-vivo, a small effect size means VRET performed comparably to the gold-standard in-vivo therapy.</p>
<p>___________</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px;">[1] A systematic review with a meta-analysis is a study in which the author(s) aggregate other studies, combine data from these studies, and analyze the results. The benefits of these studies are you get a more robust data set, and can come to a conclusion if there are studies with competing findings. The downside of these studies is often you are stuck trying to combine heterogenous data sets.</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px;">______________</p>
<p>So the findings that most support VRET would be a large effect size when compared to placebo, and a small effect size compared to in-vivo. The below chart has the study findings:</p>
<div data-hs-responsive-table="true" style="overflow-x: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 100%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; font-size: 16px;">
<table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; table-layout: fixed; border: 1px solid #99acc2; height: 316px;">
<tbody>
<tr style="height: 117px;">
<td style="width: 27.477%; padding: 4px; border-color: #444444; border-style: solid; text-align: left; height: 117px;"><strong>Pathology</strong></td>
